hands_on_practices.solution:
We start from the driven damped oscillator equation in steady-state, whose amplitude as a function of driving frequency $\omega$ is
$$A(\omega)\;=\;\frac{F_0}{\sqrt{(k-m\omega^2)^2+(b\,\omega)^2}}\,. $$
The static displacement under a constant force $F_0$ is
$$x_{\rm static}\;=\;\frac{F_0}{k}\,. $$
At resonance $\omega=\omega_0$ we have $k-m\omega_0^2=0$, so
$$A(\omega_0)=\frac{F_0}{b\,\omega_0}\,. $$
The amplification factor is the ratio of these two displacements:
$$\frac{A(\omega_0)}{x_{\rm static}}
=\frac{\dfrac{F_0}{b\,\omega_0}}{\dfrac{F_0}{k}}
=\frac{k}{b\,\omega_0}
=\frac{m\,\omega_0^2}{b\,\omega_0}
=\frac{m\,\omega_0}{b}
=Q\,. $$
